title: Dressing
en: Dress to match the venue; smart casual suits most places; follow posted dress codes for fine-dining.

title: Arriving on Time
en: Arrive on time, especially with a booking.

title: Waiting for Party
en: Wait for all guests to arrive before being seated if required.

title: Booking Ahead
en: Make a reservation in advance for popular restaurants.

title: Seating Order
en: Respect seat arrangements; host/important guests at head positions.

title: No Items on Table
en: Fine-dining etiquette: keep phones and personal items off the table; switch to silent and take calls outside.

title: No Texting
en: Do not text at the table; excuse yourself if you must take a call.

title: Dietary Needs
en: Tell the restaurant your dietary requirements and any allergies when booking or before ordering; for severe allergies, call ahead.

title: Agree Split Bill
en: Confirm how the bill will be split before dining.

title: Matching Courses
en: Match the group's pace; consider ordering a similar number of courses; if you prefer fewer, ask the server to pace your meal.

title: Napkin Etiquette
en: Place your napkin on your lap; on the chair if leaving temporarily.

title: Wait Before Eating
en: Wait for everyone’s meal to arrive before eating.

title: Cutlery Hands
en: Keep knife in right hand, fork in left; do not switch.

title: Resting Cutlery
en: Place knife and fork parallel on right side of plate when finished.

title: Moderate Volume
en: Keep voice at moderate volume; avoid loud talking.

title: Hands on Lap
en: Keep elbows off the table; rest your hands in your lap or lightly on the table between bites

title: Passing Left
en: When sharing, pass dishes in one consistent direction; follow the flow your table starts; there’s no fixed left/right rule in Australia.

title: Politeness
en: Treat wait staff politely; say please and thank you.

title: Discreet Feedback
en: Do not criticize food loudly; politely explain if returning a dish.

title: Patience
en: Be patient; do not rush the service.

title: Toasting
en: Common toast is 'Cheers'; also 'To your health'.

title: Rounds Culture
en: At pubs, expect rounds or 'a shout' culture of buying drinks.

title: No Business Talk
en: Avoid business talk unless the host initiates.

title: Respecting Diets
en: Respect diverse diets: vegetarian, halal, gluten-free, etc.

title: Alternative Utensils
en: Ask for alternative utensils (e.g., chopsticks) if needed.

title: Sharing Plates
en: Portions may be large; consider sharing or ordering small plates.

title: Asking Takeaway
en: Ask politely for takeaway if food is unfinished.

title: Shared Tables
en: In casual restaurants you may share a table; greet politely.

title: Tipping
en: Tipping is not mandatory in Australia; only in fine dining.
